"Leng Q., Langlois G.A., Yang H.","Early Paleogene Arctic terrestrial ecosystems affected by the change of polar hydrology under global warming: Implications for modern climate change at high latitudes",2010,"Science China Earth Sciences","53","7",,"933","944",,,10.1007/s11430-010-3081-5,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-77954533374&partnerID=40&md5=83330e23326f5c87c16c5cf3c8df0f3b","Department of Science and Technology, College of Arts and Sciences, Bryant University, Smithfield, RI 02917, United States; LPS, Nanjing Institute of Geology and Palaeontology, Chinese Academy of Sciences, Nanjing 210008, China","Leng, Q., Department of Science and Technology, College of Arts and Sciences, Bryant University, Smithfield, RI 02917, United States, LPS, Nanjing Institute of Geology and Palaeontology, Chinese Academy of Sciences, Nanjing 210008, China; Langlois, G.A., Department of Science and Technology, College of Arts and Sciences, Bryant University, Smithfield, RI 02917, United States; Yang, H., Department of Science and Technology, College of Arts and Sciences, Bryant University, Smithfield, RI 02917, United States","Our understanding of both the role and impact of Arctic environmental changes under the current global warming climate is rather limited despite efforts of improved monitoring and wider assessment through remote sensing technology. Changes of Arctic ecosystems under early Paleogene warming climate provide an analogue to evaluate long-term responses of Arctic environmental alteration to global warming. This study reviews Arctic terrestrial ecosystems and their transformation under marked change of hydrological conditions during the warmest period in early Cenozoic, the Paleocene and Eocene. We describe a new approach to quantitatively reconstruct high latitudinal paleohydrology using compound-specific hydrogen isotope analysis which applies empirically derived genus-specific hydrogen isotope fractionations to in situ biomolecules from fossil plants. We propose a moisture recycling model at the Arctic to explain the reconstructed hydrogen isotope signals of ancient high latitude precipitation during early Paleogene, which bears implications to the likely change of modern Arctic ecosystems under the projected accelerated global warming. © Science China Press and Springer-Verlag Berlin Heidelberg 2010.","Arctic ecosystems; Global hydrology; Global warming; Paleogene climate; Vegetation change","Arctic terrestrial ecosystems; Cenozoic; Environmental change; Fossil plant; Global hydrology; High Latitudes; Hydrogen isotope; Hydrological condition; In-situ; New approaches; Paleo-hydrology; Paleocene; Paleogene; Paleogene climate; Remote sensing technology; Vegetation change; Warming climate; Environmental impact assessments; Global warming; Hydrogen; Hydrology; Isotopes; Remote sensing; Vegetation; Water; Ecosystems; arctic environment; Cenozoic; climate variation; Eocene; global warming; hydrogen isotope; paleobiogeography; Paleocene; paleoclimate; paleoecology; paleoenvironment; Paleogene; paleohydrology; reconstruction; terrestrial ecosystem; vegetation cover; Arctic",,,,,,"Steffen, W., Sanderson, A., Tyson, P.D., (2004) Global Change and the Earth System: A Planet Under Pressure, p. 336. , Berlin-Heidelberg-New York: Springer-Verlag; Mann, M.E., Zhang, Z., Hughes, M.K., Proxy-based reconstructions of hemispheric and global surface temperature variations over the past two millennia (2008) Proc Natl Acad Sci USA, 105, pp. 13252-13257; (2007) Synthesis Report. Valencia, p. 104. , The Core Writing Team of IPCC. Climate Change, Spain: IPCC (International Panel on Climate Change); Frakes, L.A., Francis, J.E., Syktus, J.I., (1992) Climatic Modes of the Phanerozoic, p. 274. , Cambridge: Cambridge University Press; Christie, R.L., McMillan, N.J., Tertiary fossil forests of the Geodetic Hills, Axel Heiberg Island, Arctic Archipelago (1991) Geo Surv Can Bull, 403, pp. 1-226; Greenwood, D.R., Basinger, J.F., The pal